communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This situation sounds like it could be annual ryegrass toxicity (ARGT). ARGT is very common, causes a more serious disease than ryegrass staggers, and results in more loss of livestock. Ryegrass staggers is not so common in Australia, although it is in the USA. Ryegrass staggers is not necessarily deadly. Believing the disease is ryegrass toxicity, not ryegrass staggers, then ARGT is associated with ingestion of toxins (corynetoxins) present in _Lolium rigidum_ (annual ryegrass) and not _L. perenne_ (perennial ryegrass).

The toxins of _L. rigidum_ have a mysterious origin, in that they are produced by the bacterium _Rathayibacter toxicus_, which infects _L. rigidum_ via its vector, the nematode _Anguina funesta_.

Victoria, Australia is located on the interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2492476,288. - Mod.TG]
